    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Black-figure kylikes characterized by miniature decoration; generally of the 7th and early 6th centuries BCE. They also feature a slightly offset lip, a moderately deep bowl, and a very tall stem and foot. The little master cup was one of the forms to predominate in black-figure until about 540 BCE. Ther term comes from the English translation of the German word 'kleinmeister.'</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046899/Clark, Elston and Hart, Understanding Greek Vases (2002)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Kylixes de figuras negras caracterizados por decoraciones de miniaturas; generalmente del siglo VII y comienzos del siglo VI AC. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Zwartfigurige kylikes die worden gekenmerkt door miniatuurdecoratie. Gewoonlijk daterend uit de 7de en het begin van de 6de eeuw v. Chr. Ook kenmerkend is een enigszins naar buiten stekende rand, een vrij diepe kom, en een zeer lange steel en voet. De kleinmeisterschaal was tot circa 540 v. Chr. een van de meest voorkomende zwartfigurige vormen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052476/Allard Pierson Museum</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>以微型裝飾著稱的黑繪雙耳盞，一般見於西元前七世紀至六世紀初期。其特色包括略為收窄的杯口，杯身深度適中，握柄及杯腳皆高，，直至西元前540年皆是黑繪器皿最常見的形式之一；此詞彙從德文「kleinmeister」翻譯成英文而來。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Schwarzfigurige Kylix mit miniaturartiger Bemalung, üblicherweise aus dem 7. und frühen 6. Jh. v. Chr. Die Form besteht aus einer leicht abgesetzten Lippe, einer moderat tiefen Schale und einem Fuß mit sehr hohem Schaft. Die Kleinmeisterschale war eine vorherrschende Form in schwarzfiguriger Vasenmalerei bis etwa 540 v. Chr.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
